             was Indicted for a Misdemeanor in <rs id="t16951014-28-off156" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t16951014-28-off156" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16951014-28-off156" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp>
               Cheating the 
                     <persName id="t16951014-28-victim91" type="victimName">Bank of England<interp inst="t16951014-28-victim91" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t16951014-28-off156 t16951014-28-victim91"></join>
                     </persName>
                   of 720l. on the <rs id="t16951014-28-cd157" type="crimeDate">10th day of June</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t16951014-28-off156 t16951014-28-cd157"></join> last, for that he with one Price not yet taken, and one Randal, did contrive to get a little Money Honourably, as they called it
            </rs>. It appeared thus, Davis forged a false Writing in the Name of Charles Lloyd called a Title, and forged the Common Serjeant's Hand to it, pretending that Charles Lloyd had an Interest in the Chamber of London of 1858l. 9s. 2d. of which he claimed in the Right of his Wife Mary, Daughter and Orphan of 
               <persName id="t16951014-28-person92">
                  Richard 
                  Sidney
               <interp inst="t16951014-28-person92" type="surname" value="Sidney"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16951014-28-person92" type="given" value="Richard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16951014-28-person92" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             Mercer, deceased; which Title he brought to the Bank, and desired to know whether the Bank would lend Money on Orphan's Interest, and being told that the Bank would lend 40l. per Cents Which being agreed upon, they directed him to go to the Common Serjeant's Office and make an Assignment of his Interest, and accordingly he goes and forges an Assignment subscribed Charles Lloyd, purporting that he had assigned his Interest to Sir 
               <persName id="t16951014-28-person93">
                  Thomas 
                  Abney
               <interp inst="t16951014-28-person93" type="surname" value="Abney"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16951014-28-person93" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16951014-28-person93" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , Kt. 
               <persName id="t16951014-28-person94">
                  Obadiah 
                  Sedgwick
               <interp inst="t16951014-28-person94" type="surname" value="Sedgwick"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16951014-28-person94" type="given" value="Obadiah"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t16951014-28-person94" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
